I've been working on adding login shell support to PowerShell in https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/pull/10050.

One of the optimisations I've been trying to add is a short circuit at startup so we don't check for login twice.

The idea we settled on was to set an environment variable, which for the purposes of this issue looks like this:

```csharp
static void DoPowerShellLogin()
{
        if (Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("ALREADY_CHECKED_LOGIN") != null)
        {
            return;
        }

        Environment.SetEnvironmentVariable("ALREADY_CHECKED_LOGIN", "1");
        exec("/path/to/pwsh", new string[] { null });
}

[DllImport("libc")]
private static extern int exec(string path, string[] args);
```

In the debugger, this successfully created the environment variable in the first pass, but on the other side of the `exec` call it wasn't defined.

I played with this a bit and eventually tried a direct invocation of the `setenv` syscall:


```csharp
static void DoPowerShellLogin()
{
        if (Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("ALREADY_CHECKED_LOGIN") != null)
        {
            return;
        }

        setenv("ALREADY_CHECKED_LOGIN", "1", true);
        exec("/path/to/pwsh", new string[] { null });
}

[DllImport("libc")]
private static extern int exec(string path, string[] args);

[DllImport("libc")]
private static extern int setenv(string name, string value, bool overwrite);
```

And this now worked.

Most interestingly, before calling `exec` but after calling `setenv`, `Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("ALREADY_CHECKED_LOGIN")` returned `null`.

I'm assuming this behaviour is by design, but I'm not really sure why it is the way it is; I certainly didn't expect `setenv` to work when `Environment.SetEnvironmentVariable()` didn't.

Mechanical/automated change.  The only manual changes were a) removing the two rules from the CodeAnalysis.ruleset file, b) removing spaces from one line of a .targets file that is used to generate a .cs file, and c) reverting the changes in a few test files where the naive replacement happened in the middle of a verbatim string where the whitespace actually mattered.

Changes were made via:
```C#
using System;
using System.IO;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        foreach (string path in Directory.EnumerateFiles(@"d:\repos\corefx\src\", "*.cs", SearchOption.AllDirectories))
        {
            bool modified = false;
            string[] lines = File.ReadAllLines(path);

            // Remove whitespace from end of lines
            for (int i = 0; i < lines.Length; i++)
            {
                string line = lines[i];
                int spaces = 0;
                for (int c = line.Length - 1; c >= 0; c--)
                {
                    if (!char.IsWhiteSpace(line[c])) break;
                    spaces++;
                }
                if (spaces > 0)
                {
                    lines[i] = line.Substring(0, line.Length - spaces);
                    modified = true;
                }
            }

            // Remove ending blank lines
            int endingBlankLines = 0;
            for (int i = lines.Length - 1; i >= 0; i--)
            {
                if (!string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(lines[i])) break;
                endingBlankLines++;
            }
            if (endingBlankLines > 0)
            {
                lines = lines.AsSpan(0, lines.Length - endingBlankLines).ToArray();
                modified = true;
            }

            if (modified)
            {
                File.WriteAllLines(path, lines);
                Console.WriteLine(path);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

